{
    "if-content": {
        "title": "(으)면 (if,when)",
        "content": [
            {
                "title": "When we want to say a conditional sentence in Korean, a sentence that carries the meaning 'if', then we have to conjugate the Korean verb that we are using 'if' with, by replacing the '다' stem with (으)면.",
                "details": "1. If the verb ends in a consonant, then we replace the verb stem with 으면.<br/>2. If the verb ends in a vowel, then we replace the verb stem with 면.<br/>3. To emphasize the 'if' meaning, we can add the word '만약' at the beginning of the sentence.<br/>4. Like in English, we should say something after, because we said 'if' so we also need to explain what happens."
            }
        ],
        "button": "<p><a href='#!/lesson/level2/should' class='btn btn-primary btn-prev btn-lg' role='button'>Previous lesson</a><a href='#!/lesson/level2/honorific' class='btn btn-primary btn-next btn-lg' role='button'>Ok, next lesson</a></p>"
    },
